  <subsection xml:id="subsec-magfld_movcharge">
    <title> Magnetic Field of a Moving Charge: </title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
       	<me>
          \vec{B} =\frac{\mu_{o}}{4\pi}\frac{q\vec{v}\times\hat{r}}{r^{2}}  \quad 	(Vector)
        </me>
        <me>
          B =\frac{\mu_{o}}{4\pi}\frac{qv\sin\phi}{r^{2}}  \quad    	(Magnitudes) 
        </me>
            </p>
    </introduction>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-free_permblt">
      <title>Permeability of Free Space, <m>\mu_{o}</m></title>
      <p>
        The property of space which permit magnetic flux to pass through it is known as permeability. 
        It is a measure of relative increase or decrease in the resultant magnetic field inside 
        a material compared with the magnetizing field H in which the given material is located. 
        It is a constant of proportionality that exists between magnetic induction (magnetic 
        flux density) B and magnetic field intensity (magnetizing field) H. For free space 
        <me>
          \mu_{o}= 4\pi\times10^{-7} \,W_{b}/A.m 
        </me>
         	<me>
            = 4\pi\times10^{-7} \,Henry/m = 1.2566\times10^{-6} \,H/m 
          </me>
          	<me>
              c =\frac{1}{\sqrt{\epsilon_{o}\mu_{o}}}
            </me>
           Materials may be classified magnetically on the basis of their permeabilities. 
           Materials that cause the lines of flux to move farther apart, resulting in a 
           decrease in magnetic flux density compared with a vacuum, are called <term>diamagnetic</term>. 
           Materials that concentrate magnetic flux by a factor of more than 1 but less than or equal 
           to 10 are called <term>paramagnetic</term>; materials that concentrate the flux by a 
           factor of more than 10 are called <term>ferromagnetic</term>. The  permeability 
           factors of some substances change with rising or falling temperature, or with the intensity 
           of the applied magnetic field. Permeability is often expressed in relative, rather than in 
           absolute, terms. If <m>\mu_{o}</m> be the permeability of free space, <m> \mu</m> be the 
           permeability of the given substance, then the relative permeability, <m>\mu_{r} </m>, is given by:
           <me>
            \mu_{r} = \frac{\mu}{\mu_{o}} 
           </me>
             </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-biot_savrt">
      <title>Magnetic Field of a Current Element (Biot Savart Law)</title>
      <p>
        <me>
          \vec{dB} =\frac{\mu_{o}}{4\pi}\frac{I\vec{dl}\times\hat{r}}{r^{2}} \quad (Differential) 
        </me>
        <me>
          \vec{B} =\frac{\mu_{o}}{4\pi}\int\frac{I\vec{dl}\times\hat{r}}{r^{2}} \quad (Integral)
        </me>
          </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-stwire_magf">
      <title>Magnetic Field of a straight wire</title>
      <p>
        <me>
          \vec{\,dB} =\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{2a}{x\sqrt{x^{2}+a^{2})}}  \quad  	\text{(Right Hand Rule)} 
        </me>
        <me>
          B = \frac{\mu_{o}I}{2\pi r}\quad  	\text{(Right Hand Rule)}
        </me>
             </p> 
             <figure>
              <caption></caption>
              <sidebyside widths="35% 35%">
                <figure xml:id="fig51">
                  <caption></caption>
                  <image source="fig51.png"/>
              </figure>
                  <figure xml:id="rtgripmag">
                      <caption></caption>
                      <image source="rtgripmag.png"/>
                  </figure>
                   </sidebyside>
            </figure>
             <p>
              Consider a current carrying straight conductor of length  2a.  
              To find a magnetic field at a point P from the conductor consider a small current 
              element <m> \,dy</m> on a conductor and use Biot-Savart's law, 
              <me>
                \vec{\,dB}=\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{\vec{\,dy}\times\hat{r}}{r^{2}} (-\hat{k})
              </me>
              The direction of magnetic field at  P  is given by right hand grip rule which is going 
              into the plane of the paper. <m>\hat{r} </m> is unit vector along <m>\vec{r}</m> 
              and <m>\theta</m> is angle between current element and line joining the current element to point P. 
              <me>
                \text{or,}\quad \,dB=\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{\,dy\sin\theta}{r^{2}} 
              </me>
              <me>
                =\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{x}{r}\frac{\,dy}{r^{2}} = \frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{x\,dy}{r^{3}} 
              </me>
              <me>
                =\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{x\,dy}{(x^{2}+y^{2})^{3/2}}
              </me>
              <m>[\because \quad r^{2}=x^{2}+y^{2}]</m>
              <men xml:id="eqn-biot1">
                \therefore \quad B = \int \,dB=\frac{\mu_{o}I x}{4\pi}\int\limits_{-a}^{a}\frac{\,dy}{(x^{2}+y^{2})^{3/2}} 
              </men>
            Now solve the integrand first with the help of geometry of the figure then substitute the value to obtain B. 
            <me>
              \tan\phi = \frac{y}{x}
            </me>
            <me>
              \text{or,}\quad y=x\tan\phi
            </me>
            <me>
              \text{or,}\quad \,dy=x\sec^{2}\phi\,d\phi
            </me>
            <me>
              \therefore \quad \mathscr{I} = \int \frac{\,dy}{(x^{2}+y^{2})^{3/2}} 
            </me>
            <me>
              = \int \frac{x \sec^{2}\phi\,d\phi}{\left[x^{2}(1+\tan^{2}\phi)\right]^{3/2}}
            </me>
            <me>
              = \int\frac{x\sec^{2}\phi\,d\phi}{x^{3}\sec^{3}\phi} = \frac{1}{x^{2}}\int\cos\phi\,d\phi
            </me>
            <me>
              \text{or,}\quad \mathscr{I} = \frac{1}{x^{2}}\sin\phi 
            </me>
            <me>
              =\frac{1}{x^{2}}\frac{y}{r} =\frac{y}{x^{2}\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            <ol marker="a.">
              <li>
                <me>
                  \therefore \quad B = \frac{\mu_{o}I x}{4\pi}\left[\frac{y}{x^{2}\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}\right]_{-a}^{a}
                </me>
                <me>
                  =\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi} \left[\frac{2a}{x\sqrt{x^{2}+a^{2}}}\right]
                </me>
              </li>
              <li> 
                When <m> x \lt \lt a</m> (ie., for infinitely long wire) then <m> 1 \lt \lt \frac{a}{x} </m>, hence
                <me>
                  B = \frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi} \left[\frac{2a}{x\cdot x\sqrt{1+\frac{a^{2}}{x^{2}}}}\right] 
                </me>
                <me>
                  = \frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{2a}{x^{2}\sqrt{\frac{a^{2}}{x^{2}}}} =\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi} \frac{2a}{x}
                </me>
                <me>
                  \therefore \quad  B=  \frac{\mu_{o}I }{2\pi x} 
                </me>
                  </li> 
                  <li>
                    When <m> x \gt \gt a</m> then <m>\frac{x}{a} \gt \gt 1</m>, hence  
                    <me>
                      B =  \frac{\mu_{o}I }{2\pi} \frac{a}{x^{2}} \simeq 0 
                    </me>
                      </li>
            </ol>
                 </p>
    </subsubsection>

